Use asupersync two-phase reserve/commit pattern for cancel-safe database transactions.

## Why Two-Phase
In standard async code, if a task is cancelled between BEGIN and COMMIT:
- Transaction is left open (connection leak)
- Partial writes may be visible if using autocommit
- ROLLBACK may not execute (task already gone)

Asupersync two-phase pattern prevents this:
- Phase 1 (reserve): Acquire write permit, begin transaction — cancel-safe
- Phase 2 (commit): Execute writes, commit — must complete (linear/masked)

## Design
Create a DatabaseTransaction wrapper:

struct DbTransaction<'a> {
    conn: &'a Connection,
    committed: bool,
}

impl DbTransaction {
    async fn reserve(cx: &Cx, pool: &ConnectionPool) -> Outcome<DbTransaction> {
        let conn = pool.acquire(cx).await?;  // Cancel-safe
        conn.execute("BEGIN CONCURRENT")?;
        Outcome::ok(DbTransaction { conn, committed: false })
    }

    fn execute(&self, sql: &str) -> Result<()> {
        self.conn.execute(sql)
    }

    fn commit(mut self) -> Result<()> {
        self.conn.execute("COMMIT")?;
        self.committed = true;
        Ok(())
    }
}

impl Drop for DbTransaction {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        if !self.committed {
            let _ = self.conn.execute("ROLLBACK");
        }
    }
}

## Integration Points
- Collector ingestion: reserve before batch insert, commit after all rows
- Audit logging: reserve before audit event, commit after
- Vacuum operations: reserve before DELETE, commit after verification

